<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="319" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,222,391]" pageId="4" pageNumber="319">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haldeman" authorityYear="1847" box="[151,288,222,247]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Hyperplatys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="319" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,288,222,247]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="319">Hyperplatys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has eleven species currently assigned to the genus. All are distributed in the Western Hemisphere: six in the Neotropical region and five in North America (
<bibRefCitation box="[788,941,259,283]" pageId="4" pageNumber="319" refId="ref5649" refString="Monne, M. A. (2018) Catalogue of the Cerambycidae (Coleoptera) of the Neotropical region. Part II. Subfamilies Lepturinae, Necydalinae, Parandrinae, Prioninae, Spondylidinae, Oxypeltidae, Vesperidae, Disteniidae. Available from: http: // cerambyxcat. com / (accessed 30 March 2018)" type="url">Monn√© 2018</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[956,1315,258,283]" pageId="4" pageNumber="319" refId="ref5744" refString="Tavakilian, G. &amp; Chevillotte, H. (2017) Titan: base de donnees internationales sur les Cerambycidae ou Longicornes. Version 3.0. Available from: http: // titan. gbif. fr / (accessed 30 March 2018)" type="url">Tavakilian &amp; Chevillotte 2017</bibRefCitation>
). Previous studies of this genus (
<bibRefCitation box="[394,534,294,319]" pageId="4" pageNumber="319" refId="ref5044" refString="Dillon, L. S. (1956) The Nearctic components of the tribe Acanthocinini (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Part III. Annals of the Entomological Society of America, 49 (4), 332 - 355. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / aesa / 49.4.332" type="journal article">Dillon 1956</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[546,670,295,319]" pageId="4" pageNumber="319" refId="ref5204" refString="Horn, G. H. (1880) Notes on some genera of Cerambycidae with descriptions of new species. Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 8, 115 - 138. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 25076387" type="journal article">Horn 1880</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[682,972,294,319]" pageId="4" pageNumber="319" refId="ref5360" refString="Linsley, E. G. &amp; Chemsak, J. A. (1995) The Cerambycidae of North America. Part VII, No. 2. Taxonomy and classification of the subfamily Lamiinae, tribes Acanthocinini through Hemilophini. University of California, Publications in Entomology, 114, 1 - 292." type="journal article">Linsley &amp; Chemsak 1995</bibRefCitation>
), which included only the fauna of North America, compared 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haldeman" authorityYear="1847" box="[380,517,330,355]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Hyperplatys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="319" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[380,517,330,355]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="319">Hyperplatys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName authority="Bates, 1863" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1863" box="[555,810,330,355]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Lepturges" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="319" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[555,666,332,355]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="319">Lepturges</emphasis>
Bates, 1863
</taxonomicName>
, differentiating the former principally by the prosternal process broader, and elytra with distinct lateral carina.
</paragraph>
